Project Overview

Research Agenda

What is your research agenda/objective/question?

My research involves a data set of 80 different cereals. It includes health information of the cereal such as calories, macronutrients, micro nutrients,servings and rating. My agenda involves investigating which cereal mfr has the most highly rated cereal and if it is a matter of advertising or flavor profile. Could it be that certain macronutrient profiles have a much higher probability of having a higher rating? is does volume of servings matter? I also want to take into account the vitamins and minerals that these cereals have and see if people choose cereal more for taste or health.

Data Source and Description

This data is a breakdown of 80 cereals with their dietary characteristics. Each record represents a cereal type and includes a macro/micro nutrient breakdown of each cereal. In addition, information relating to the serving size and weight is also included.

Rows/Observations in the Data

calories: represents gram amount of calories in cereal protein: represents gram amount of protein in cereal per serving fat:represents gram amount of fat in cereal per serving sodium:represents gram amount of sodium in cereal per serving fiber:represents gram amount of fiber in cereal per serving carbo:represents gram amount of carbohydrates in cereal per serving sugars:represents gram amount of sugars in cereal per serving potass:represents gram amount of potass in cereal per serving vitamins:represents gram amount of vitamins in cereal per serving shelf:represents shelf rank 1-3 by level weight: represents gram weight per serving cups: represents amount of cups per serving rating: rating of cereal in percentage

The Population

In most cases, a data set can be considered as a sample from a population. How would you characterize the population from which this sample was taken? Be specific (e.g All adults in the USA vs just all adults.)

The population of the sample taken would be cereal consumers in the united states who had the ability to comment and rate the Cereals in the data set.

Histogram distribution of calories in cereals

# A filed barplot with the composition of macronutrients of the cereal. Filtered based off lower levels of fiber.

cereals_data_small <- Cereals_Data %>% 
  filter(fiber<6) %>%              # filtered "unhealthy" cereal based off amount of fiber. The FDA averaged cereal to have a fiber content of 6 grams per serving. I assumed that anything less of the average was less healthy.
  select(mfr, protein,fat,carbo)

cereals_small_tidy <- cereals_data_small %>% 
  pivot_longer(cols = c(protein, fat, carbo),      
               names_to = "macro_nutrient_factor",      
               values_to = "grams")  

ggplot(data = cereals_small_tidy, mapping = aes(x = mfr, y = grams, fill = macro_nutrient_factor)) +
  geom_col(width = 0.5, position = position_dodge(0.7))

# The composition of most cereals by manafacturer appears to be a large amount of carbohydrates 10 to 12 grams, followed by a small amount of protein  of roughly 4 grams and a small sum of fats approximately 3 grams. 
# A filed barplot with the composition of macronutrients of the cereal.

# Regression analysis

#Fiberiber had a higher level, eliminated potassium for regression analysis.

lm(rating ~ sugars, data = Cereals_Data)
## 
## Call:
## lm(formula = rating ~ sugars, data = Cereals_Data)
## 
## Coefficients:
## (Intercept)       sugars  
##      59.284       -2.401
# an increase of 1 in grams of sugar implies an decrease of 2.401 in cereal rating score

lm(rating ~ fiber, data = Cereals_Data)
## 
## Call:
## lm(formula = rating ~ fiber, data = Cereals_Data)
## 
## Coefficients:
## (Intercept)        fiber  
##      35.257        3.443
# an increase of 1 in grams of fiber implies an increase of 3.443 in cereal rating score

# Sugar and Fiber seem to be the determing factors regarding the overall rating score of the cereal via a linear regression.
#A bar graph distribution of the average calories of cereal by manafacturer. The lower end suggests about 85 calories while the upper bound appears to be 115. The average is roughly 105.


cereal_calories_by_mfr <- Cereals_Data %>% 
  group_by(mfr) %>% 
  summarize (
    avg_cereal_calories = mean(calories))

glimpse(cereal_calories_by_mfr)

ggplot(data = cereal_calories_by_mfr, aes(x = mfr, y = avg_cereal_calories)) + 
  geom_col()

# Final conclusion, most cereal seem to have the same compostion in regards to macro-nutrients and calories. What seems to determine the higher level ratings is higher levels of fiber, this could be due to people wanting to have better digestion as cereal tends to be a morning meal. On the other hand, higher sugar levels seem to have a negative effect on the rating. Thus could be due to the fact that since cereal is a morning meal people would opt out eating something with higher levels of sugar as it will spike insulin and cause irregularities in energy levels throughout the day.
